3. Mathematical Conditions for Emergence

Emergence arises when these four conditions are satisfied:

Condition 1 ‚Äî Compression Pressure

The system seeks minimum-description-length (MDL) representations.

Formally:

\min_{v_t} L(v_t) \quad \text{subject to continuity}

where L is description length.

Condition 2 ‚Äî Attractor Availability

NTE defines attractor basins A_i.

Emergence occurs when the trajectory enters a basin:

v_t \in \text{basin}(A_i)

Condition 3 ‚Äî Cross-Manifold Coupling

Bees, Spiders, Dragonfly, and Hound daemons induce manifold coupling:

v_{t+1} = v_t + \sum_i \beta_i \nabla f_i(v_t)

Where f_i are domain-specific potentials.

Condition 4 ‚Äî Stability of Fixed Points

PantheonOS converges to stable fixed points:

\nabla \mathcal{E}(v^*) = 0

These represent emergent behaviors:
